name: Jim Fitterling
text: There are no easy fixes. No silver bullets. Just a lot of good people companies, groups, societies, and consumers around the world collaborating with each other to make a difference: a more sustainable world.

name: Jim Fitterling
text: Once we get the infrastructure right where we're not letting plastics go to waste we must close the loop. Example: Our partnership w/ @FuelSolutionW2E. They'll provide us pyrolysis oil feedstock, made from recycled plastic waste. We'll use it to produce new polymers.

name: Jim Fitterling
text: All of these must work together simultaneously to make this effort effective. It's heavy on collaboration. We have a bias toward action. And we're agnostic about where the solutions come.

name: Jim Fitterling
text: And, as a result, we are driving progress in 4 key areas: Infrastructure development Education and engagement Innovation Clean up

name: Jim Fitterling
text: @EndPlasticWaste which @DowNewsroom is a founding member of is doing just that. It's probably the most coordinated & comprehensive waste management effort undertaken since the mid-1970s & we are working w/ partners all around the world to develop local solutions.

name: Jim Fitterling
text: The first step, then, is to stem the tide of trash bleeding into the rivers and the oceans. There are 10 rivers on the globe mostly in Southeast Asia that deliver 90% of plastics waste into our oceans. We cannot let plastics go to waste in the first place.

name: Jim Fitterling
text: To #endplasticwate, we're going to root cause of the problem the lack of infrastructure in some critical places and the lack of an efficient closed-loop, #circularyeconomy system.
